For `ẋ = f(x)` with equilibrium at `x = 0`, choose a `C^1` Lyapunov function `V` such that `V(0)=0`, `V(x)>0` for `x≠0` near `0`, and `V` is radially bounded on a neighborhood; along trajectories, compute `V̇(x)=∇V(x)·f(x)` and show `V̇(x) ≤ 0` near `0`; then every sublevel set `{x: V(x) ≤ c}` sufficiently close to `0` is forward invariant, so trajectories starting sufficiently near `0` remain near `0`, which proves Lyapunov stability; if in fact `V̇(x) < 0` for all `x≠0` near `0`, the same argument strengthens to asymptotic stability.
